Our system must operate within the Operations Security (OPSEC) framework (DoD Directive 5205.02 and Manual 5205.02-M), ensuring that sensitive medical logistics data—classified as Controlled Unclassified Information (CUI)—is protected from exposing critical operational indicators such as blood shortages, degraded hubs, route vulnerabilities, and casualty projections, all of which could be exploited by adversaries. To mitigate this, the system must enforce encrypted communications, role-based access control, and compliance with NIST SP 800-171, limiting access to authorized users and preventing data leakage, while aligning with the DHA and Armed Services Blood Program to maintain chain of custody, traceability, temperature control, and testing validation standards comparable to U.S. FDA requirements. Front-facing users should only see aggregated or risk-based information rather than exact inventory, locations, routes, or projections, as OPSEC prioritizes mission survivability over detail, while HIPAA ensures patient privacy when applicable. Operationally, blood must be stored at 34–39°F with strict cold-chain management, as red blood cells last 35–42 days, platelets 5–7 days, and plasma up to one year frozen (24 hours once thawed), requiring systems to track expiration, implement FIFO (first in first out), and flag redistribution windows (e.g., <5 days) to move supply to high-demand areas. Refrigeration reliability, including power redundancy and transport cooling, is critical, and while dry ice may support frozen plasma transport (5–10 lbs per 24 hours), more sustainable solutions include phase-change materials and portable powered refrigeration. Overall, the system must balance predictive logistics, waste reduction, and secure data handling while incorporating strong cybersecurity measures such as network hardening, patch management, and endpoint protection.
